<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-686-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 686 050.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  July 30 1990 v12 n31 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Specifying drive type with partition software can be fatal. (TechTalk) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The collision of Microsoft Windows 3.0, third-party partitioningsoftware and the Smart Drive disk cache can result in a mixed-upfile allocation table (FAT) and loss of hard disk data.andO;Fortunately, this problem can be prevented.andP;  The problem stemsfrom the original IBM PC AT, which made no provision for a 'soft'specification of a drive's physical size.andP;  One method used toovercome this shortcoming creates a troubling interaction betweenDOS and sophisticated multitasking disk-caching programs such asSmart Drive.andP;  This method should not be followed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Partitioned FilesDisk CachingDrivesDefectsGuidelines.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>